##Summary

This book proposes the Non-Infinity Theory, challenging traditional misconceptions about “infinity.” What we often call “infinity” is frequently a human misunderstanding of complexity and the unknown. In reality, everything in the universe follows finite logic, structure, and cycles.

From observations in mathematics, physics, to everyday life, phenomena that appear infinite actually arise from highly complex but finite systems. For example, seemingly endless time and space may in fact be multi-layered, dynamic cycles. Stillness might also be a form of microscopic cycling, and time may not be linear but spiral-shaped, reshaping our experience.

Non-Infinity Theory is not only a reconsideration of the universe’s structure but also offers profound philosophical insights:
•   Nothingness is not absolute emptiness but a hidden structure awaiting activation.
•   The laws governing the world are not a single linear path but multi-layered, relative cycles.
•   Even if everything follows patterns, we still have room for choice.

The truth of the universe is neither singular nor absolute. To understand this multi-layered, dynamic cosmic structure, we must let go of binary thinking and ego attachment. Just as time can be both linear and relative, it all depends on the perspective from which we observe.

Once we understand that “nothingness is not a stable void, but a hidden structure containing the potential for ending and transformation—and that when it reaches its limit, existence naturally emerges in response,” we can infer that nothingness itself is unstable. Within it lies the potential for change and conclusion. This suggests that the birth of the universe was not a random miracle, but a logical necessity. When nothingness reaches its extreme, some form of existence must inevitably arise.

Therefore, Non-Infinity Theory offers a new way to understand the origin of the universe—not as something that emerged from “absolute nothing,” but from a state of “hidden void structured with mechanisms of conclusion and transformation.”

The universe will eventually come to an end, but this is not a message of despair. Instead, it gives greater meaning to our existence. Because of finiteness, every moment of ours is worth cherishing. And true meaning lies in the clarity and experience of the present moment.
